TY  - JOUR
T1  - Hot Spots and Blind Spots: Geographical Clusters of Firms and Innovation
AU  - Pouder, Richard
AU  - St. John, Caron H.
Y1  - 1996/10/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1996.9704071867
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1996.9704071867
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 1192
EP  - 1225
VL  - 21
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Hot spots are fast-growing geographic clusters of competing firms. Drawing on several literature streams, we develop an evolutionary model that contrasts hot spot and non-hot spot competitors within the same industry. Initially, economies of agglomeration, institutional forces, and managers' mental models create an innovative environment within the hot spot. Over time, those same forces create a homogeneous macroculture that suppresses innovation, making hot spot competitors more susceptible than non-hot spot competitors to environmental jolts.
AB  - Hot spots are fast-growing geographic clusters of competing firms. Drawing on several literature streams, we develop an evolutionary model that contrasts hot spot and non-hot spot competitors within the same industry. Initially, economies of agglomeration, institutional forces, and managers' mental models create an innovative environment within the hot spot. Over time, those same forces create a homogeneous macroculture that suppresses innovation, making hot spot competitors more susceptible than non-hot spot competitors to environmental jolts.
