TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Role of Strategic Reference Points in Explaining the Nature and Consequences of Human Resource Strategy
AU  - Bamberger, Peter
AU  - Fiegenbaum, Avi
Y1  - 1996/10/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1996.9704071859
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1996.9704071859
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 926
EP  - 958
VL  - 21
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examine how managers use strategic reference points (SRPs) or benchmarks to guide their strategic decision making with regard to human resource (HR) issues and how these benchmarks can affect the performance-based consequences of such decisions. After describing the reference points that are relevant to the HR system, we develop propositions regarding the likely configuration of such reference points and their impact on the nature of HR policies and practices. We also explain how the management of SRP fit and consensus can reduce the likelihood that HR policies and practices will have a negative effect on a firm's performance. Organizationwide implications are discussed.
AB  - We examine how managers use strategic reference points (SRPs) or benchmarks to guide their strategic decision making with regard to human resource (HR) issues and how these benchmarks can affect the performance-based consequences of such decisions. After describing the reference points that are relevant to the HR system, we develop propositions regarding the likely configuration of such reference points and their impact on the nature of HR policies and practices. We also explain how the management of SRP fit and consensus can reduce the likelihood that HR policies and practices will have a negative effect on a firm's performance. Organizationwide implications are discussed.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1996.9704071859
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1996.9704071859
Y2  - 2026/04/24
